Variables and Data Types in Java (Simple Explanation)
1Ô∏è‚É£ What is a Variable?
A variable is like a container that stores data. In Java, every variable has a name, type, and value.

üîπ Example:

java
Copy
Edit
int age = 25;  // 'age' is a variable storing the value 25
Here,

int ‚Üí Data type (stores whole numbers)
age ‚Üí Variable name
25 ‚Üí Value stored in the variable
2Ô∏è‚É£ Types of Variables in Java
Java has three types of variables:

Type	Description	Example
Local Variable	Declared inside a method and used only within it.	int x = 10; inside a method
Instance Variable	Declared inside a class but outside methods. Each object gets its own copy.	String name; inside a class
Static Variable	Shared across all objects of a class (declared using static).	static int count = 0;
3Ô∏è‚É£ Data Types in Java
Data types define what kind of values a variable can store. Java has two main types:

A. Primitive Data Types (8 types)
Data Type	Size	Stores	Example
byte	1 byte	Small whole numbers (-128 to 127)	byte b = 100;
short	2 bytes	Medium whole numbers (-32,768 to 32,767)	short s = 30000;
int	4 bytes	Large whole numbers (-2B to 2B)	int num = 100000;
long	8 bytes	Very large whole numbers	long bigNum = 9999999999L;
float	4 bytes	Decimal numbers (less precision)	float pi = 3.14f;
double	8 bytes	Decimal numbers (high precision)	double precisePi = 3.141592;
char	2 bytes	Single character	char letter = 'A';
boolean	1 bit	true or false values	boolean isJavaFun = true;
B. Non-Primitive Data Types (Objects, Strings, Arrays, etc.)
Data Type	Example
String	String name = "Venkatesh";
Array	int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
Class	class Car {}
4Ô∏è‚É£ Example Program:
java
Copy
Edit
public class DataTypeExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 25;  // Integer variable
        double price = 99.99;  // Decimal variable
        char grade = 'A';  // Character variable
        boolean isPassed = true;  // Boolean variable
        String name = "Venkatesh";  // String (non-primitive)

        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Age: " + age);
        System.out.println("Grade: " + grade);
        System.out.println("Passed: " + isPassed);
        System.out.println("Price: " + price);
    }
}
5Ô∏è‚É£ Summary
Variables store data in Java.
Primitive types (8) store simple values like numbers and characters.
Non-primitive types store complex objects like Strings and Arrays.
