Packages


Packages in Java (Simple Explanation)
What is a Package?
A package in Java is like a folder that organizes related Java files together. It helps to:
‚úÖ Avoid name conflicts
‚úÖ Make code reusable and manageable
‚úÖ Provide access control

Example: Why Use Packages?
Imagine you have two classes named Student‚Äîone for school records and another for college records. Without packages, Java gets confused.

‚úÖ Solution? Put them in different packages.

Copy
Edit
school.Student
college.Student
How to Create and Use Packages?
1. Creating a Package
Use the package keyword at the top of the Java file.

java
Copy
Edit
package mypackage;  // Package name

public class Hello {
    public void sayHello() {
        System.out.println("Hello from mypackage!");
    }
}
üìå Save this file as Hello.java inside a folder named mypackage.

2. Using a Package in Another Class
To use a class from a package, we use import.

java
Copy
Edit
import mypackage.Hello;  // Import the Hello class from mypackage

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Hello obj = new Hello();
        obj.sayHello();
    }
}
Types of Packages
1Ô∏è‚É£ Built-in Packages ‚Äì Java‚Äôs pre-defined packages (e.g., java.util, java.io)
2Ô∏è‚É£ User-defined Packages ‚Äì Custom packages created by developers

Example: Built-in Package (java.util)
java
Copy
Edit
import java.util.Scanner; // Importing Scanner class

public class BuiltInExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter your name: ");
        String name = sc.nextLine();
        System.out.println("Hello, " + name);
    }
}
Summary
‚úÖ Packages are like folders that organize Java classes.
‚úÖ Use package to define a package.
‚úÖ Use import to use a class from another package.
‚úÖ Java has built-in packages (like java.util) and user-defined packages.
