Package 
Packages in Java (Simple Explanation)
A package in Java is like a folder that helps organize your Java files (classes, interfaces, etc.). It groups similar types of classes together, making the code structured, reusable, and easy to manage.

Why Use Packages?
Avoids Name Conflicts ‚Äì Two classes can have the same name if they are in different packages.
Organizes Code ‚Äì Helps keep related classes together.
Provides Access Control ‚Äì Some classes can be hidden from other packages.
Reusability ‚Äì We can use existing packages in multiple projects.
Types of Packages in Java
Built-in Packages ‚Äì These are already available in Java (e.g., java.util, java.io).
User-defined Packages ‚Äì Created by programmers to organize their own code.
How to Create a Package?
Declare a package at the top of the Java file
Save the file in a folder with the same package name
Example:

java
Copy
Edit
package mypackage;  // Creating a package named "mypackage"

public class Hello {
    public void greet() {
        System.out.println("Hello from mypackage!");
    }
}
How to Use a Package?
To use a class from another package, we use the import keyword.

Example:

java
Copy
Edit
import mypackage.Hello;  // Importing the Hello class from "mypackage"

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Hello obj = new Hello();  // Creating an object of Hello
        obj.greet();  // Calling the method
    }
}
Common Built-in Packages
java.util ‚Üí For utility classes (e.g., ArrayList, Scanner).
java.io ‚Üí For input/output operations (e.g., reading/writing files).
java.net ‚Üí For network-related operations.
